The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, April 10, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, April 9: NIIT Ltd will hold a 25 per cent stake in its technology arm, NIIT Technologies Ltd (NTL), after the proposed restructuring. The company is also planning to list NTL on the stock exchanges. The parent company proposes to hold a 25 per cent stake in NTL after the spin-off, which is expected to be completed by June-end, NIIT chief executive Vijay K. Thadani said. The demerger was aimed at creating focused entities, having the necessary flexibility to pursue their individual growth strategies, he added. The scheme of arrangements had received shareholders consent on March 24 and the company is awaiting Delhi high courts approval. 																								 New Delhi, April 9: State-owned TCIL has 30 days to decide whether it wants to block Bhartis second attempt to acquire a stake in Hexacom by exercising its right of first refusal. The board would meet shortly to take a view on this.																								 Washington, April 9: US trade representative Robert Zoellick, in his review of telecom trade agreements around the world, has said that market access barriers existed in the form of restrictions in countries, including India, Germany, Switzerland and Singapore.																								 New Delhi, April 9: ONGC plans to increase capacity of its subsidiary, Mangalore Refinery and Petrochemicals Ltd, to 15 million tonnes at an investment of Rs 2000 crore by 2007.																								 Seoul, April 9: Hyundai Motor is in talks to sell a significant stake in Hyundai Capital Services Consumer Finance unit to an outside company, vice-chairman Kim Dong Jin said. He declined to name the other company involved in the talks.
